                            <p><b>Introduction </b></p>
                            <p>When we talk about net zero energy consumption, we're referring to the idea that your home should operate like a "free" one. You'll save money by not paying for electricity or gas. In addition to this, you'll also be doing your part for the environment by reducing your carbon footprint and being carbon neutral.</p>
                            <p><b>Reduce carbon footprint</b></p>
                            <p>Reducing your carbon footprint is an important part of reducing your energy consumption. The more you can do to reduce the amount of energy you use, the fewer impacts companies and industries have on global warming and climate change.</p>
                            <p>In addition to reducing waste, it's also important to use renewable energy sources such as solar or wind power when possible so that you're not contributing environmentally harmful greenhouse gases into the atmosphere.</p>
                            <p>If you’re looking to reduce your carbon footprint, there are many things you can do. The first step is to analyze your current energy consumption by using an energy audit of your building. (Could use our Carbon Book app) This will identify the amount of energy being used and measure it.</p>
